{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f25c9d9d-d1a4-42cf-a005-bad14e4fac77","content":"There's no relevant documentation in this repository, so here's general guidance:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump`. On macOS, use the OS-level mechanisms instead:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash reports** — macOS automatically writes crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before running your app:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Core files are written to `/cores/` (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n3. **If `/cores/` is missing or permission-denied**, create it:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **For richer .NET diagnostics**, you can also use `dotnet-dump analyze` on the core file if the .NET diagnostic tooling supports the NativeAOT runtime version you're targeting.\n\n> **Key point:** On macOS, `kern.corefile` and SIP settings can prevent core dumps. Run `sysctl kern.corefile` to check the path, and note that on newer macOS versions you may need to disable SIP or use `lldb` to attach live instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"60e3316a-61ac-4e99-a374-95a16c537345","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository appears to be empty or doesn't contain relevant documentation. Let me answer from general knowledge about macOS crash dump recovery for NativeAOT apps.","outputTokens":433,"requestId":"640F:131578:15B6598:1938ACF:69EC1A60"},"id":"2d5c9c0d-4d8f-4d40-8236-fe4bca4f03b4","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:35:39.134Z","parentId":"54a46047-9a5b-4d4f-900d-65d7295e8422"}
